n Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"St.","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."],"variants":[{"name":"St","meanings":["Americanized spelling of French   St  .   Denis  ."]},{"name":"Denis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Jacques, Armand, Marcel, Andre, Pierre, Serge, Yvan, Alphonse, Edouard, Francois, Gaetane.  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Jorge, Roberto, Angel, Francisco, Joaquin, Juan, Manuel, Miguel, Ramon, Rolando.","French, Walloon, Breton, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, Dutch, English, and Portuguese; Spanish and Galician (<b>Denís</b>): from the personal name <i>Denis</i>, Spanish and Galician <i>Denís</i>, from Latin <i>Dionysius</i> ‘(follower) of Dionysos’ (see   Dennis  ). Compare   Dennee  .","Ukrainian and Rusyn: variant transliteration of   Denys  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"Claire","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Clare  .","Variant of   Clair  , an altered form of German   Klare  .","French: variant of   Clair  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Klaric","meanings":["Croatian (<b>Klarić</b>) and Slovenian (<b>Klarič</b>): metronymic from the female personal name <i>Klara</i> (see   Claire  )."]},{"name":"Clare","meanings":["Irish (Clare, Wicklow, and Wexford): habitational name from Clare in Suffolk (an eastern county of England), the center of a major Norman baronial estate since the Norman Conquest. The English placename probably originated as a Celtic river name meaning ‘bright, gentle, or warm’. The surname is not from the Irish county name <i>Clare</i>, which is either from the surname or from a place called with Gaelic <i>clár</i> ‘plank bridge’. Another Norman surname in the southeast of Ireland was <i>de Clere</i>, from Clères in Seine-Maritime (France), named from the local river.","English and French: from the Middle English, Old French female personal name <i>Cla(i)re</i> (from Latin <i>Clara</i>, from <i>clarus</i> ‘clear, bright, famous’) which achieved some popularity, greater elsewhere in Europe than in England, through the fame of Saint Clare of Assisi (see   Chiara  ). The English surname seems to have been interchangeable with   Clear   1.","English: occupational name from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>cley</i> ‘clay’. The work of medieval clayers involved plastering a framework of interwoven twigs with mud to produce wattle-and-daub work."]}]},{"name":"Felice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Roman family name <i>Felix</i> ‘lucky’.  See  <b>Felix</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Felice de St. Claire was born about 1142, in Ashley, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, WILLIAM DE ST CLAIR, was -14 and her mother, Mrs. Katherine De St Claire, was 26. She married Walter de Esselegh I. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter."},"et":{"Abt 1142–":"umbes 1142–Surnud","1142–Female":"1142–Surnud","1140–1195":"1140–1195","1164–1246":"1164–1246","1180–1252":"1180–1252","1157–Male":"1157–Surnud","1117–Female":"1117–Surnud","Abt 1142":"umbes 1142","1117":"1117","1246":"1246","1157":"1157","1252":"1252","1164":"1164","1142":"1142","1195":"1195","1140":"1140","about 1164":"umbes 1164","1180":"1180","Ashley, Wiltshire, England":"Ashley, Wiltshire, England","Cheltenham, Cheltenham district, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheltenham, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Ashley, Box, Wiltshire district, Wiltshire,